The park includes historic cotton textile mills, 5.6 miles of canals, operating gatehouses, and worker housing.
Turn-of-the-century trolleys operate March through November.
The park will be closed Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day, and New Year's Day.
[EMBED]
Visitor Center Begin your visit at Market Mills, the former Lowell Manufacturing Company mill complex, one of the city's original textile mills.
Market Mills houses the National Park Visitor Center, where you can make reservations for tours, explore exhibits, visit the Children's Corner, and view the award-winning multi-image video program, "Lowell: The Industrial Revelation" every half hour 9:00 AM - 4:00 PM Also on view at 4:30 PM is "Lowell Blues," a film by Henry Ferrini about author Jack Kerouac and his native city.
(Due to special programs, times may vary occasionally).
General information on area lodging, cultural institutions, and dining is also available.
Also in Market Mills: the Visitor Center Bookstore, and the Brush Art Gallery and Studios.
Boott Cotton Mills Museum Don't miss the roar of a 1920s weave room with operating power looms! The Boott Cotton Mills Museum includes the weave room plus interactive exhibits and video programs about the Industrial Revolution, labor, and the rise, fall, and rebirth of Lowell.
Adults, $4.00; Youths, 6-16 
Closed December 24th.
Also at the museum, check for daily happenings at the Tsongas Industrial History Center, Lowell Historical Society, and shop at the Museum Store (reduced hours in winter - call for details) for a large selection of mill-related books, cloth from our weave room, books for kids, and other mill-related items.
Patrick J. Mogan Cultural Center The Patrick J. Mogan Cultural Center, located at 40 French Street, is a program of Lowell National Historical Park in partnership with the University of Massachusetts Lowell.
The mission of the Mogan Cultural Center is to "tell the human story of Lowell" through the development of exhibits, projects and programs.
The Center serves as the home to the world-renowned Angkor Dance Troupe, LNHP's Mill Girls and Immigrants Exhibit and the University of Massachusetts' Center for Lowell History.
The Mogan Cultural Center strives to play a positive role among community groups as well as advance cultural and historical activities within the city.
Acropolis of America III: Passing the Torch Opens Sunday, October 19, 2003.
This third exhibit will cover the years 1940 to 1974 and will complete coverage of the first 100 years of Hellenic settlement in the Lowell Massachusetts area.
Sponsored by the Lowell Hellenic Heritage Association.
City Lives: Immigrants to Lowell Saturday, January 31, 2004 - March, 2004 This exhibit is the fourth in a series documenting the lives of the citizens of Lowell and will feature photographs and biographies of immigrants from over 15 nations.
Native American Ways March, 2004 - October, 2004 The past and present of the Native peoples of the Greater Lowell area.
Sponsored by the Greater Lowell Indian Cultural Association.
Other Events Join the staff of the Center for Lowell History for ongoing genealogy workshops on Tuesdays from 5:00 to 9:00 PM and learn how to trace your family tree.
Workshops run from October through May.
For more information please call the Center at 978-934-4997.
Mill Girls and Immigrants Exhibit Explore the history of "mill girls" and immigrants in a Boott Mill boardinghouse.
The Mill Girls and Immigrants Exhibit, located in the Patrick J. Mogan Cultural Center, tells the human story of the Industrial Revolution by concentrating on the working people of Lowell.
Free.
Closed December 24th.
The park is closed on Thanksgiving, Christmas, and New Year's Day
